Resampling Techniques on Imbalanced Iris Dataset

This project evaluates the impact of different resampling techniques on an imbalanced version of the Iris dataset using a neural network model. The dataset contains flower measurements as features and class labels with unequal class distribution.

A Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) classifier with two hidden layers is used as the learning model. Performance is evaluated using 2-fold cross-validation to ensure consistent comparison across all methods.

Part 1: Imbalanced Dataset

The model is first trained and evaluated on the original imbalanced dataset. Metrics such as confusion matrix, standard accuracy, class-balanced accuracy, and balanced accuracy are computed to highlight the effect of class imbalance on performance.

Part 2: Oversampling

Oversampling techniques are applied to increase the number of samples in minority classes:

Random Oversampling
SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique)
ADASYN (Adaptive Synthetic Sampling)

Each method generates a more balanced dataset, and the model is evaluated to observe improvements in classification performance.

Part 3: Undersampling

Undersampling techniques are used to reduce the number of samples in majority classes:

Random Undersampling
Cluster Centroids
Tomek Links

These methods aim to balance the dataset by removing or refining majority class samples, and their impact on model performance is analyzed.

Metrics Reported
Confusion Matrix
Accuracy Score
Class-Balanced Accuracy
Balanced Accuracy
Tech Stack
Python
NumPy
Pandas
scikit-learn
imbalanced-learn
